title: Q Is Playing Chess
text:
By stompk (Reporter)
Tuesday, January 23, 2018 11:12
% of readers think this story is Fact. Add your two cents.
Julian Assange posted a tweet with a picture of a Chess game already in play. At first, it was confusing, but then someone figured out it was a specific game in history.
This was a game played in 1918 between Jose Capablanca and Frank Marshall. Marshall, an American, was the underdog. At this point in the game, they were at move 24. Black (Capablanca) had just moved bishop back to infront of Queen. The next move by Marshall (White) was unexpected and is now famously known as the Marshall attack.
White Queen to F3. This set Marshall up for the win…
You see, Q posted about the Atlanta airport shutdown, and someone asked if they re-located a pawn or a bigger player. Q answered BISHOP
Atlanta went dark (Black) and Bishop was moved. ie, black bishop move #24 in chess game, so next move would be Queen to F3 or the Marshall Attack.
That was in the Fox 3 Splash string. F3.
Now, genius chess anon put a whole thread together to explain his methods. 
The next move is Black Rook (CASTLE) to e3
Every [3] letter is here. You are in the middle of something historic. Q
DR_noon_clear_sky^ Safe comms_SAT-re_Bz985300^00
e_
e3
Now, this is the next to the last move in the game. Next. Marshall (white) moves bishop to take pawn.
At this point, the game is over. White keeps black in check until checkmate, so Capablance resigns (quits)
Black rook takes white bishop, white rook puts black king in check, black king has to move diagonally, white queen takes black rook, BK moves to corner, white queen take pawn, checkmate…
But, here’s where it gets interesting. The Keystone.
ps, W&W = Wizards and Warlocks. And yes, Keystone = NSA+Potus/USMil + QAnon warriors. But everything has double or more meanings, as pointed out by Q.
So, what is the Keystone. Could it be the stone of destiny?
The following video is rather long but fascinating. A rabbit hole in itself.

Capablanca was playing white, not black. Marshall playing black had pushed white’s king all over the board but Capablanca defended perfectly and went on to win. After the black rook takes bishop, white “queens” his pawn to put black in check and now has 2 queens on the board and wins quickly. See the youtube: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaUHECHqcWs for details. The point is that white is beaten all over the board but ultimate wins especially with the strong Qf3 or queen to fox 3 move. Capablanca defeats the infamous “Marshall attack” in a come-from-behind brilliant sequence.
